Lets start with a simple truthan affidavit isnt just a piece of paper; its a sworn statement
that carries the weight of truth. Without a signature, that sworn statement is like a house without
a foundation, it's just going to fall apart when tested. To establish probable cause, an affiant
must swear to the facts of the case under penalty of perjury. This is not optional. Its required
ensure that no one is unjustly accused or deprived of their liberty without proper verification.
The affidavit at the heart of this case is missing this signature. Without it, the case simply
doesnt hold water.

@Shane Before we proceed, I must ensure you understand your rights in this matter:

1. You have the right to remain silent. This means you do not have to speak or provide any information that could incriminate you.

2. You also have the right to have an attorney present during any questioning or legal proceedings. If you cannot afford an attorney, one will be appointed for you at no cost.

3. You have the right to a fair and public trial, where evidence will be presented, and witnesses can be called to testify on your behalf.

4. Furthermore, you have the right to confront witnesses against you, meaning you can question them in court.

5. Finally, you have the right to appeal any conviction or sentence imposed upon you.

OFFENSE TYPE - FELONY

meowiitten 2025-04-09 10:43 p.m.
Youve entered pleas of guilty to two felony offenses. This Court will accept those pleas. As to Count ISecond-Degree Murder under 1 M.S.C. 2102you are now convicted. As to Count IIAssault with a Deadly Weapon under 1 M.S.C. 2302you are also convicted.

Here is the sentence of the Court:

On Count I, I sentence you to forty minutes in the custody of the Department of Corrections. That term begins today. You are further prohibited from holding, seeking, or maintaining peace officer status for fifty days under 4 M.S.C. 1601(d). You may petition for expungement of this convictioneight months from todaypursuant to 5 M.S.C. 1 1503.1. Whether that petition is granted is a matter for another day.

On Count II, you are sentenced to one month of probation. That runs concurrent to the sentence on Count I. You may not serve as a peace officer during that timesame bar, same statute, same fifty days. You are subject to direct supervision by the Clark County Sheriff and his deputies. You will not carry a weapon, not associate with known felons, not violate the law. You will follow directions, submit to searches, wear the monitor if ordered, meet when told, and stay clean.

I will be clear on this next part as well: if any agency or actor, military or civilian, attempts to skirt this sentence, this Court will respond. If you are given a firearm, a badge, a post, a dutyany position of powerduring your disqualification period, you will be brought back before me.

I have written a Memorandum Opinionattached to and incorporated into the Sentencing Order just entered. It sets forth, in full, the basis for this judgment. That opinion is final, and it is appealable. If any party intends to file a motion to reconsider, modify, or to vacate the sentence, please do not wait. I expect it within ten days.

That concludes sentencing.
